oxton, Bedfordshire, England","Shropshire,  or Cornwall":"Shropshire, England","Cornwall or Shropshire":"Shropshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"ABT 1321–":"about 1321–Deceased","1321–Female":"1321–Deceased","1315–Male":"1315–Deceased","1330–1397":"1330–1397","1340–1373":"1340–1373","1366–Male":"1366–Deceased","1301–1349":"1301–1349","1300–Female":"1300–Deceased","17 JUN 1994":"17 June 1994","1330":"1330","1373":"1373","1340":"1340","1346 to 1366":"from 1346 to 1366","Abt 1340":"about 1340","1349":"1349","1315":"1315","12 APR 1995":"12 April 1995","25 JUN 1994":"25 June 1994","1301":"1301","ABT 1342":"about 1342","1366":"1366","1300":"1300","ABT 1321":"about 1321","1321":"1321","1397":"1397","about 1321":"about 1321","Of, Blakemore, Herefordshire, England":"Blakemere, Herefordshire, England, United Kingdom","Roxton, Bedfordshire, England":"Roxton, Bedfordshire, England","Shropshire,  or Cornwall":"Shropshire, England","Cornwall or Shropshire":"Shropshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Strange","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Wiltshire and Gloucestershire): nickname for a newcomer to a district, from Middle English <i>strange</i> ‘foreign’ (Old French <i>estrange</i>, Latin <i>extraneus</i>, from <i>extra</i> ‘outside’).","Irish (Antrim): this name is also common in Ireland, where, in addition to its English etymology, it may represent an Anglicized form of any of several Irish names containing the element <i>gall</i> ‘stranger’, e.g.   Doyle  ,   Gallagher  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Stranger","meanings":["English: nickname for a newcomer to an area, from Middle English <i>stra(u)nger(e)</i> ‘stranger, foreigner’ (Old French <i>estrangier</i>). Compare   Strange  ."]},{"name":"Doyle","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Sean, Kieran, Seamus, Aileen, Dermot, Liam, Niall, Brennan, Brigid, Conal, Conan, Donal.","Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Dubhghaill</b> ‘descendant of <i>Dubhghall</i>’, a personal name composed of the elements <i>dubh</i> ‘black’ + <i>gall</i> ‘stranger’. This was used as a byname for Scandinavians, in particular to distinguish the darker-haired Danes from fair-haired Norwegians. Compare   McDougall  ,   McDowell  ."]},{"name":"Lestrange","meanings":["Irish and English: variant of   Strange   1 with fused Old French definite article <i>le</i>.","Irish: in Ireland, adopted for <b>Mac Conchoigchríche</b> ‘son of <i>Cúchoigcriche</i>’, a personal name meaning ‘hound of the borderland’. <i>Lestrange</i> was adopted for <b>Mac Conchoigchríche</b> probably due to the presence of a prominent family of Lestrange, of similar meaning, who settled in the counties of Westmeath and Offaly in the 16th century."]}]},{"name":"Maude","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Variant of   Maud  , the usual spelling of the name in North America."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Le","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Lewis   or respelling of   Lou  , as borne by the impresario  Lew Grade  (  1906–98 , originally  Louis Winogradsky )."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Maude Le Strange was born about 1321, in Blakemere, Herefordshire, England, United Kingdom, her father, Robert Le Strange, was 21 and her mother, Baroness Alinore, was 23. She married Sir Brian Cornwall MP about 1342, in Blakemere, Herefordshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter."},"et":{"ABT 1321–":"umbes 1321–Surnud","1321–Female":"1321–Surnud","1315–Male":"1315–Surnud","1330–1397":"1330–1397","1340–1373":"1340–1373","1366–Male":"1366–Surnud","1301–1349":"1301–1349","1300–Female":"1300–Surnud","17 JUN 1994":"17. juuni 1994","1330":"1330","1373":"1373","1340":"1340","1346 to 1366":"1346 kuni 1366","Abt